''Adventure'' received mostly positive reviews in the years immediately after its release and has generally been viewed positively since then.

Norman Howe reviewed ''Adventure'' in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' No. 31.<ref name="SG">{{cite journal|last=Howe|first=Norman |date=September 1980 |title=Capsule Reviews|journal=[[The Space Gamer]]|publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]]|issue=31|pages=27}}</ref> Howe commented that "''Adventure'' is a good game, as video games are measured. It is neither as interesting nor as complex as ''Superman'', but it shows great promise for things to come."<ref name="SG"/>

[[Bill Kunkel (journalist)|Bill Kunkel]] and Frank Laney in the January 1981 issue of ''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'' called ''Adventure'' a "major design breakthrough" and that it "shatters several video-game conventions" such as scoring and time limits. They added that it was "much more ambitious" than average home video games, but the graphics were underwhelming, such as the hero being a square.<ref>{{cite journal | first1=Bill | last1=Kunkel | first2=Frank | last2=Laney | title=Arcade Alley: Atari's 'Adventure' | page=28 | journal=[[Video (magazine)|Video]] |date=January 1981}}</ref> The 1982 book ''How to Win at Home Video Games'' called it too unpredictable with an "illogical mission", concluding that "even devoted strategists may soon tire of ''Adventure''{{'}}s excessive trial and error."<ref name=htwahvg>{{cite book | title=How to Win at Home Video Games | page=59 | publisher=Publications International | year=1982}}</ref> ''[[Electronic Games]]'' in 1983 stated that the game's "graphics are tame stuff", but it "still has the power to fascinate" and that "the action adventure concepts introduced in ''Adventure'' are still viable today".<ref name="eg198306">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/electronic-games-magazine-1983-06/Electronic_Games_Issue_16_Vol_02_04_1983_Jun#page/n45/mode/2up | title=The Players Guide to Fantasy Games | work=Electronic Games | date=June 1983 | access-date=January 6, 2015 | pages=47}}</ref> A separate review from 1983 in the magazine's ''[[Electronic Games|Electronic Games 1983 Software Encyclopedia]]'' awarded the game a 9 out of 10 rating, praising its gameplay and single player gaming as excellent and outstanding respectively while only finding its graphics and sound as merely "good".<ref name="eg1983">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Electronic Games|Electronic Games 1983 Software Encyclopedia]]|title=Atari 2600 (VCS)|issn=0736-8488|publisher=Reese Communications|year=1983|volume=1|issue=1|page=16}}</ref>

Jeremy Parish of ''[[1UP.com]]'' wrote in 2010 that ''Adventure'' is "a work of interpretive brilliance" that "cleverly extracted the basic elements of exploration, combat and treasure hunting from the text games and converted them into icons", but also conceded that it "seems almost unplayably basic these days".<ref name="1up">{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-adventure |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524035145/http://www.1up.com/features/essential-50-adventure |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 24, 2011 |title=The Essential 50 Part 4 – Adventure |publisher=1UP.com |year=2010 |first=Jeremy |last=Parish |access-date=December 17, 2012 }}</ref>

Atari Headquarters scored the game 8 of 10, noting its historical importance while panning the graphics and sound, concluding that ''Adventure'' was "very enjoyable" regardless of its technological shortcomings.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.atarihq.com/reviews/2600/adventure.html | first=Adam | last=King | title=AGH Atari 2600 Review: Adventure | publisher=Atari Headquarters | access-date=April 25, 2014 | archive-date=January 21, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121195642/http://www.atarihq.com/reviews/2600/adventure.html | url-status=live }}</ref> In 1995, [[Flux (magazine)|Flux]] magazine ranked Adventure 35th on their Top 100 Video Games. They described the game as: "challenging and incredibly fun."<ref>{{Cite journal |date=April 1995 |title=Top 100 Video Games |url=https://archive.org/details/flux-issue-4/page/n29/mode/2up |journal=Flux |publisher=Harris Publications |issue=4 |pages=28}}</ref>

==Legacy==
Considered one of the first [[action-adventure video game]]s<ref name=IGN>{{cite web | url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/903/903024p1.html | first=Levi | last=Buchana | title=Top 10 Best-Selling Atari 2600 Games | date=August 26, 2008 | publisher=[[IGN]] | access-date=December 3, 2009 | archive-date=July 26, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726161836/http://retro.ign.com/articles/903/903024p1.html | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Adventure Before Adventure Games: A New Look at Crowther and Woods's Seminal Program | journal = [[Games & Culture]] | first1 = Jonathan | last =Lessard | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages =119-135 | doi =  10.1177/1555412012473364 | date = February 21, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/business-32079749 | title = Scotched eggs: Is this the death of the Easter egg? | date = April 3, 2015 | accessdate=  June 25, 2024 | work = [[BBC News]] | first = Padraig | last = Belton }}</ref> and fantasy games for consoles,{{r|eg198306}} ''Adventure'' established its namesake genre on video game consoles.{{sfn|Bogost, Montfort|2009|p=16|ref=Beam}} In addition to being the first graphical adventure game on the Atari 2600 console,<ref name=wolf2008>{{cite book | author=Wolf, Mark J. P. | title=The Video Game Explosion: A History from PONG to Playstation and Beyond | page=82 | year=2008 | publisher=ABC-CLIO | isbn=978-0-313-33868-7}}</ref> it is the first video game to contain a widely known Easter egg, and the first to allow a player to use multiple, portable, on-screen items while exploring an open-ended environment, making it one of the first examples, even as small and primitive as it is, of an [[open world]] game.<ref name="theory">{{cite book | editor=Mark J.P. Wolf, Bernard Perron | title=The Video Game Theory Reader | page=vii | year=2013 | publisher=Routledge | isbn=978-1-1352-0518-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/1902/game_design_essentials_20_open_.php?print=1 | title = Game Design Essentials: 20 Open World Games | first = John | last = Harris | date = September 26, 2007 | access-date = July 31, 2016 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | archive-date = August 16, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190816134347/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/1902/game_design_essentials_20_open_.php%3Fprint%3D1 | url-status = live }}</ref> The game is the first to use a ''[[fog of war]]'' effect in its catacombs, which obscures most of the playing area except for the player's immediate surroundings.{{sfn|Bogost, Montfort|2009|pp=58–59|ref=Beam}}

The game has been voted the best Atari 2600 game in numerous polls,<ref name="theory"/> and has been noted as a significant step in the advancement of home video games.{{sfn|Wolf|2001|p=97|ref=medium}} ''[[GamePro]]'' ranked it as the 28th most important video game of all time in 2007.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.gamepro.com/gamepro/international/games/features/110049.shtml | title=Feature: The 52 Most Important Video Games of All Time | magazine=[[GamePro]] | page=3 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070521071406/http://www.gamepro.com/gamepro/international/games/features/110049.shtml | archive-date=May 21, 2007}}</ref> In 2010, ''[[1UP.com]]'' listed it as one of the most important games ever made in its "The Essential 50" feature.<ref name="1up"/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named ''Adventure'' as one of the top 10 games for the Atari 2600.<ref>{{Cite magazine | url = http://www.ew.com/article/2013/01/25/the-10-best-atari-games | title = The 10 Best Atari Games | first = Aaron | last = Morales | date = January 25, 2013 | access-date = April 5, 2016 | magazine = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | archive-date = January 15, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180115174334/http://ew.com/article/2013/01/25/the-10-best-atari-games/ | url-status = live }}</ref>

A sequel to ''Adventure'' was first announced in early 1982. The planned sequel eventually evolved into the [[Swordquest|''Swordquest'' series]] of games.<ref name="Phosphor">{{cite web |last = Green |first = Earl |title = Atari 2600 Adventure |publisher = Phosphor Dot Fossils |url = http://www.thelogbook.com/phosphor/atari26/q1-05/index.htm |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060507075952/http://www.thelogbook.com/phosphor/atari26/q1-05/index.htm | archive-date=May 7, 2006}}</ref> In 2005, a sequel written by Curt Vendel was released by Atari on the [[Atari Flashback#Atari Flashback 2|Atari Flashback 2]] system. In 2007, [[AtariAge]] released a [[self-published]] sequel called ''[[Adventure II]]'' for the [[Atari 5200]], which is heavily inspired by the original; its name is used with permission from [[Atari|Atari Interactive]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atariage.com/software_page.html?SoftwareLabelID=2759 |title=Atari 5200 – ''Adventure II'' |publisher=AtariAge |access-date=December 17, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115121907/http://www.atariage.com/software_page.html?SoftwareLabelID=2759 |archive-date=November 15, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Robinett himself took the idea of using items from ''Adventure'' into his next game, ''[[Rocky's Boots]]'', but added the ability to combine them to form new items.{{sfn|Robinett|2006|p=713|ref=DesignReader}}

In both the 2011 novel ''[[Ready Player One]]'' and its [[Ready Player One (film)|2018 film version]] the Easter egg in ''Adventure'' is prominently mentioned as the inspiration for a contest to find an Easter egg hidden in the fictional [[virtual reality]] game OASIS, and finding the secret room within ''Adventure'' is a core plot element within both versions, with footage from the game (specifically the Easter egg) incorporated into the film version.<ref name="Ready Player One">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/15/books/ready-player-one-by-ernest-cline-review.html?_r=0 | title=A Future Wrapped in 1980s Culture | publisher=The New York Times Company | date=August 14, 2011 | access-date=April 20, 2014 | author=Maslin, Janet | archive-date=February 21, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221203651/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/15/books/ready-player-one-by-ernest-cline-review.html?_r=0 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ready-player-ones-ending-explained/1100-6457818/ | title = Ready Player One's Ending Explained | first = Michael | last = Rougeau | date = March 30, 2018 | access-date = March 30, 2018 | work = [[GameSpot]] | archive-date = March 31, 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180331040620/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ready-player-ones-ending-explained/1100-6457818/ | url-status = live }}</ref>

The [[Lego]] Atari 2600 set includes three "cartridges" and three corresponding dioramas. The diorama for ''Adventure'' has a scene of the game's castle with an egg hidden at its center, referencing the Easter egg.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/we-build-the-lego-atari-2600-console-and-it-contains-a-hidden-secret | title=We Build the LEGO Atari 2600 Console and It Contains a Hidden Secret | date=2 August 2022 | access-date=2 August 2022 | archive-date=2 August 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220802164206/https://www.ign.com/articles/we-build-the-lego-atari-2600-console-and-it-contains-a-hidden-secret | url-status=live }}</ref>

